Investigation of Global Temperatures From The Year 1875 to Present

Project 1 Abstract

This project investigates the rising global temperatures starting from the year 1875. The first investigation focuses on global mean temperatures in cities across the globe: specifically, Venice Italy, Milan Italy, and Buenaventura Colombia. Plot 3 examines the temperature trends in Italy and the USA over the years. In the second part of the project, latitudes across the northern hemisphere are analyzed to determine whether the poles or the equator are warming faster. The third part of the project explores how precipitation is affected by warming global temperatures.

Plot 1

library(tidyverse)

global <- read.csv(file.choose())
global$City <- as.factor(global$City)
global$Country <- as.factor(global$Country)


clean2 <- global %>%
  separate(dt, into = c("Year", "Month", "Day"), sep = "-") %>%
  select(-Day, -Month)

clean <- na.omit(clean2)

clean3 <- clean %>%
  select(Year, AverageTemperature)

clean4 <- clean3 %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarize(averageTemperature = mean(AverageTemperature, na.rm = T), sdTemperature = sd(AverageTemperature), SETemp = sdTemperature/sqrt(n()), tCrit = qt(0.975, n() - 1)) %>%
  filter(Year >= "1875") %>%
  mutate(MOE = tCrit * SETemp) %>%
  arrange(Year)

clean4$Year <- as.integer(clean4$Year)

ggplot(clean4, aes(x = Year, y = averageTemperature)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm) + 
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = averageTemperature - MOE, ymax = averageTemperature + MOE), width = 0.05) +
  labs(title = "Global Mean Temperature from 1875", x = "Year", y = "Mean Temperature (degrees C)") 

#lm(clean4$averageTemperature~clean4$Year)

Analysis

Plot one demonstrates the average global temperatures since 1875. As is shown in the graph there is a steady increase in global temperatures since the year 1875. Specifically, the slope for plot 1 is 0.009894.This means that the average increase per year is 0.009894 degrees Celsius.

#lm(city3$averageTemperature~city3$Year)

Analysis

These plots show average change in mean for the cities of Venice, Milan, and Buenaventura. Even when investigating specific cities there is still an evident increase in temperature over the years. The slope for the city of Venice had an average increase of 0.01091 degrees Celsius every year. The slope for the city of Milan had and average increase of 0.01074 degrees Celsius every year. The city of Buenaventura, Columbia had an average increase of 0.009612 degrees every year. Columbia is much closer to the equator than Italy is so it would be interesting to see if there is a correlation between latitude and the average increase every year in degrees Celsius. It should also be mentioned that the average temperatures in Columbia are higher, more than likely due to the fact that Columbia is closer to the equator. This would mean that it would have higher temperatures for most of the year. Both Milan and Italy have similar average temperatures with Milan being colder on average. The error bars are also noticeably bigger for the city graphs vs the global graph. This is likely due to the fact that the global data is sampling all of the cities for every year, giving us a much smaller SE which ends up giving us a smaller MOE; while the city graphs only sample from their own city so the SE will be larger.

Analysis

These plots show the average increase in temperature for the countries of Italy and USA. USA and Italy were chosen because they have similar latitudes and a correlation between latitudes and the slope of the average change in degrees Celsius over the years was being investigated. The average change in degrees Celsius was 0.009968 for Italy and 0.008466 for the US. USA had a slightly higher average temperature more than likely because USA also stretches lower than Italy. There are also many different biomes in USA that it could also affect the average temperature. The error bars are also noticeably larger for Italy. This is likely because Italy has less cities than the US in this dataset making a larger SE.

Part 2

cool <- clean %>%
  filter(Year >= 1875) %>%
  select(Year, AverageTemperature, Latitude) %>%
  filter(grepl('N', Latitude)) %>%
  mutate(northernLatitude = gsub('N', '',Latitude))

cool$northernLatitude <- as.numeric(cool$northernLatitude)

lat15 <- cool %>%
  filter(Latitude <= 15.0 & Latitude > 0.0) %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarize(averageTemperature = mean(AverageTemperature, na.rm = T), sdTemperature = sd(AverageTemperature), SETemp = sdTemperature/sqrt(n()), tCrit = qt(0.975, n() - 1)) %>%
  mutate(MOE = tCrit * SETemp) %>%
  arrange(Year) %>% 
  add_column(Latitude = "0-15")

  

lat30 <- cool %>%
  filter(Latitude <= 30.0 & Latitude > 15.0) %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarize(averageTemperature = mean(AverageTemperature, na.rm = T), sdTemperature = sd(AverageTemperature), SETemp = sdTemperature/sqrt(n()), tCrit = qt(0.975, n() - 1)) %>%
  mutate(MOE = tCrit * SETemp) %>%
  arrange(Year) %>% 
  add_column(Latitude = "15-30")


lat45 <- cool %>%
  filter(Latitude <= 45.0 & Latitude > 30.0) %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarize(averageTemperature = mean(AverageTemperature, na.rm = T), sdTemperature = sd(AverageTemperature), SETemp = sdTemperature/sqrt(n()), tCrit = qt(0.975, n() - 1)) %>%
  mutate(MOE = tCrit * SETemp) %>%
  arrange(Year) %>% 
  add_column(Latitude = "30-45")


lat60 <- cool %>%
  filter(Latitude <= 60.0 & Latitude > 45.0) %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarize(averageTemperature = mean(AverageTemperature, na.rm = T), sdTemperature = sd(AverageTemperature), SETemp = sdTemperature/sqrt(n()), tCrit = qt(0.975, n() - 1)) %>%
  mutate(MOE = tCrit * SETemp) %>%
  arrange(Year) %>% 
  add_column(Latitude = "45-60")


ggplot(lat15, aes(x = Year, y = averageTemperature)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm) +
  geom_errorbar(data = lat15, aes(ymin = averageTemperature - MOE, ymax = averageTemperature + MOE), width = 0.05) +
  labs(title = "Mean Temp 0-15 Latitude", x = "Year", y = "Mean Temperature (degrees C)") 

#lm(lat15$averageTemperature~lat15$Year)
## 0.00877

ggplot(lat30, aes(x = Year, y = averageTemperature)) +

Latitudes <- rbind(lat15, lat30, lat45, lat60)

ggplot(data = Latitudes, aes(Year, averageTemperature, col = Latitude)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm) +
  labs(title = "Average Temperatures Seperated By Latitudes", x = "Year", y = "Average Temperature" )

Latitudes <- rbind(lat15, lat30, lat45, lat60)

Analysis

For this section of the project I wrangled the data to contain only cities from the Northern Hemisphere, just for simplicity and created subsets for cities that are from 0-15 lat, 15-30 lat, etc. I decided to stop because there is not many cities past the 60 Latitude so it did not make sense to go all the way up to 90 Lat. The goal was to see whether the equator or the poles were warming up faster. The way I did this was a similar process as the previous section. The average slopes in order were, 0.00877, 0.007806, 0.009701, & 0.01159. As you can see it dips from 15-30 Lat, but then from 30-45 Lat it goes one degree above the 0-15 Lat. The 45-60 Lat has the highest average rate of change with 0.01159 degrees for every year. There certainly seems to be a trend for latitude and rate of change for the temperature over the years.

Part 3

indiaRainfall <- read.csv(file.choose())

Rainfall <- indiaRainfall %>%
  group_by(YEAR) %>%
  summarize(Rainfall = sum(ANNUAL, na.rm = T)) %>%
  arrange(YEAR)

aveRainfall <- indiaRainfall %>%
  group_by(YEAR) %>%
  summarize(averageRainfall = mean(ANNUAL, na.rm = T)) %>%
  arrange(YEAR)

ggplot(Rainfall, aes(x = YEAR, y = Rainfall)) + 
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Total Rainfall In India Since 1901", x = "Year", y = "Total Rainfall")

ggplot(aveRainfall, aes(x = YEAR, y = averageRainfall)) + 
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Average Rainfall In India Since 1901", x = "Year", y = "Total Rainfall")

#summary(lm(Rainfall$Rainfall~Rainfall$YEAR))

Analysis

I downloaded a dataset off of Kaggle that contains the Rain of India from the years 1901 to 2013. I decided to take the average and the total rainfall grouped by year in India. After plotting both graphs there was no obvious correlation between the increase in years and an increase in total or average rainfall. The goal was to see if there would be an increase in precipitation with the increase in global temperatures. India may more unchanging precipitation levels over the years because of the yearly monsoon seasons.
